            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="sga" resp="#PET1878">
                <ab>
                     <lb n="1"/><!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="3"/>--><persName><name nymRef="Tomas" type="apostle" subtype="saint">TOM<!--<milestone unit="shaft"/>-->A<!--<milestone unit="quadrant" n="4"/>-->S</name></persName> <expan><w lemma="apstal" corresp="https://dil.ie/3887"><abbr><hi rend="supraline">AP</hi></abbr><ex>STAL</ex></w></expan>
                   </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                 
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p> Thomas the Apostle</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"> 
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p><ref source="#MAC1949">Macalister (1949, 8)</ref> suggested that the abbreviation AP- may                             be for Latin <q><hi rend="italic">Apostolus</hi>, in which case the stone would be dedicatory, not a memorial : or for 
                        <hi rend="italic" corresp="https://dil.ie/3853">ab</hi>, "abbot," although there does not seem to be any record of an                           ecclesiastic of this name and rank anywhere near the place and probable time of this stone</q>. It could also be the                           Irish word <hi rend="italic">apstal</hi> 'apostle'. Compare the <ref target="https://emili.celt.dias.ie/ARM-002">Kilnasaggart</ref> inscription which mentions Peter the apostle. 
                    </p></item>                      
                       </list>
            </div>
